TICKET TITLE:
Printer Offline - Device Not Detected - Troubleshooting Process Documented

ISSUE:
User reported printer showing offline status. Unable to print documents. Printer not appearing in Devices list.

TROUBLESHOOTING STEPS PERFORMED:
1. Checked Devices → Printers & Scanners in Windows Settings
2. Verified no printers currently listed or connected
3. Confirmed printer power status (asked user to verify)
4. Checked for USB connection if applicable
5. Verified printer driver installation status

DIAGNOSTIC FINDINGS:
- Printer not detected by Windows
- No printer devices visible in Settings
- Suggests either:
  * Printer not powered on
  * USB/Network connection issue
  * Printer driver not installed
  * Printer hardware failure

RESOLUTION STEPS PROVIDED TO USER:
1. Power cycle printer (turn off 30 seconds, turn on)
2. Check USB cable/network connection
3. Go to printer manufacturer website
4. Download latest printer driver for Windows 11
5. Install driver and restart computer
6. Printer should appear in Devices list

IF PROBLEM PERSISTS:
- Check Device Manager for unknown devices
- Uninstall and reinstall printer driver
- Check printer manual for troubleshooting
- Contact printer manufacturer support
- Consider hardware replacement if driver/connection confirmed working

REAL IT SCENARIO:
Similar issues occur when:
- New printer first setup
- Printer driver corrupted
- USB cable disconnected
- Network printer loses connection
- Windows update removes driver

STATUS:
Troubleshooting Guide Provided to User

CATEGORY:
Hardware Support / Printer Troubleshooting / Peripheral Devices

TICKET TITLE:
PC Performance Degradation - Slow System Response - High Disk Activity Identified

ISSUE:
User reported system running extremely slowly. All tasks taking longer than normal. System appears unresponsive at times.

SYSTEM ANALYSIS PERFORMED:
Opened Task Manager and checked Performance metrics:

Current Resource Usage:
- CPU: 8% (Normal range)
- Memory: 4.4 GB of 7.9 GB (56% used - Acceptable)
- Disk (HDD): Fluctuating 7-98% (Very High Activity - Problem!)
- Secondary Disk: 0% (Not in use)

ROOT CAUSE IDENTIFIED:
High disk activity indicates background processes heavily using hard drive:
- Possible Windows Update running
- Antivirus full system scan
- Windows Indexing Service
- Disk defragmentation
- Temporary file cleanup
- Malware scanning

TROUBLESHOOTING STEPS TAKEN:
1. Analyzed Task Manager Performance tab
2. Identified disk as performance bottleneck
3. Checked which processes using disk (from Processes tab)
4. Explained findings to user

RESOLUTION PROVIDED:
Short-term:
- Close all unnecessary applications
- Wait for background processes to complete (may take 15-30 minutes)
- Avoid opening large files while disk is busy

Long-term:
- Upgrade HDD to SSD (biggest performance improvement!)
- Disable unnecessary Windows services
- Schedule antivirus scans for off-hours
- Clear temporary files regularly
- Check for malware

PERFORMANCE IMPROVEMENT OPTIONS:
1. Immediate: Restart computer, disable startup apps
2. Short-term: Clean disk, update drivers
3. Long-term: Upgrade HDD to SSD (massive speed boost!)

REAL IT KNOWLEDGE:
- HDD (spinning disk) is slowest part of modern PC
- SSD would make THIS system 5-10x faster
- High disk activity = Primary cause of slowness
- Often overlooked by users (they focus on RAM/CPU)

STATUS:
Root Cause Identified - Solution Provided

CATEGORY:
Performance Optimization / System Troubleshooting / Hardware Upgrade Recommendation


  
  TICKET TITLE:
Wi-Fi Connectivity Issue - Internet Connection Lost - Troubleshooting Performed

ISSUE:
User reported no internet connectivity. Unable to connect to Wi-Fi network. No network access.

TROUBLESHOOTING STEPS PERFORMED:

1. NETWORK STATUS CHECK:
   - Checked Wi-Fi icon in system tray (taskbar)
   - Verified network adapter status
   - Confirmed no active Wi-Fi connection

2. BASIC CONNECTIVITY TEST:
   - Opened Command Prompt
   - Ran: ping google.com
   - Analyzed response (success/failure)
   - Tested connectivity to remote server

3. NETWORK DIAGNOSIS:
   - Checked available Wi-Fi networks
   - Attempted to connect to known network
   - Verified correct password entered
   - Checked network signal strength

POTENTIAL ROOT CAUSES:
- Wi-Fi router offline or not broadcasting
- Network adapter disabled
- Wi-Fi driver issue
- Incorrect network password
- IP address conflict
- Network settings corrupted
- ISP outage

RESOLUTION STEPS PROVIDED:

Immediate Actions:
1. Restart Wi-Fi router (unplug 30 seconds, plug back in)
2. Enable Wi-Fi on laptop (check Airplane Mode OFF)
3. Forget network and reconnect
4. Restart computer

If problem persists:
1. Check Device Manager for Network Adapter status
2. Update network drivers from manufacturer website
3. Run Network Troubleshooter (Settings → Network)
4. Reset network settings
5. Contact ISP if router/modem offline

ADVANCED TROUBLESHOOTING:
- Use ipconfig command to check IP address
- Use ipconfig /all for detailed network info
- Use ping to test connectivity
- Check Event Viewer for network errors
- Verify router is broadcasting SSID
- Check if other devices can connect

REAL IT KNOWLEDGE APPLIED:
- Used Command Prompt (ping) for connectivity test
- Checked network adapter status
- Identified potential hardware vs software issue
- Provided systematic troubleshooting approach

COMMON CAUSES IN REAL SCENARIOS:
- 40% = Router/ISP issue
- 30% = Network driver issue
- 20% = Disabled network adapter
- 10% = Corrupted network settings

PREVENTION TIPS FOR USER:
- Note down router settings
- Keep router in cool, ventilated area
- Restart router monthly
- Update router firmware regularly
- Keep network drivers updated

STATUS:
Troubleshooting Guide Provided - Awaiting User Feedback

CATEGORY:
Network Support / Connectivity Troubleshooting / Wi-Fi Configuration

TICKET TITLE:
User Account Access - Forgotten Password - Account Recovery Procedure

ISSUE:
User unable to log into Windows account. Forgotten password. Account locked out.

USER VERIFICATION:
- Confirmed user identity via employee ID
- Asked security questions to verify ownership
- Documented in ticket for security compliance

TROUBLESHOOTING OPTIONS PROVIDED:

OPTION 1 - Microsoft Account Password Reset:
If user set up Microsoft Account login:
1. Click "I forgot my password" on login screen
2. Answer security questions
3. Receive password reset link via email
4. Create new password
5. Login with new password

OPTION 2 - Password Reset Disk:
If password reset disk was created previously:
1. Insert password reset disk
2. Click "Reset Password" on login screen
3. Follow wizard to create new password
4. Login with new password

OPTION 3 - Administrator Reset:
If admin account available on system:
1. Login to admin account
2. Go to Settings → Accounts → Other users
3. Select user account
4. Click "Reset password"
5. Create temporary password
6. Provide to user
7. User changes password on next login

OPTION 4 - IT Department Reset:
If no other options available:
1. Document request formally
2. Verify user identity through HR
3. Use IT admin account to reset password
4. Generate temporary password
5. User changes on first login
6. Document in ticket for audit trail

SECURITY PROTOCOL FOLLOWED:
✓ Verified user identity before proceeding
✓ Did not provide password over phone
✓ Generated temporary password (forces change)
✓ Documented all steps in ticket
✓ Created audit trail for compliance
✓ Advised user to use strong password

PASSWORD BEST PRACTICES PROVIDED TO USER:
- Use combination of uppercase, lowercase, numbers, symbols
- Minimum 8 characters (12+ recommended)
- Avoid personal information (names, birthdays, etc)
- Don't reuse passwords
- Consider using password manager
- Never share password with anyone
- Change password every 90 days (company policy)

PREVENTION FOR FUTURE:
- Create password reset disk now
- Set up security questions
- Use Microsoft Account login (cloud recovery)
- Write down hint (not actual password)
- Store recovery options safely

REAL IT SECURITY KNOWLEDGE:
- Password reset is common but SENSITIVE task
- Must verify identity before proceeding
- Never email/text actual passwords
- Always force password change on next login
- Document everything for audit/compliance
- Follow company security policy

COMPLIANCE NOTES:
- This request documented with timestamp
- User identity verification logged
- Password reset method documented
- Follows company security procedures
- Audit trail maintained for compliance

RELATED IT BEST PRACTICES:
- Implement Single Sign-On (SSO) where possible
- Use Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)
- Enforce strong password policies
- Regular security training for users
- Periodic password changes
- Compliance with data protection standards

STATUS:
Password Reset Completed - User Advised on Security

CATEGORY:
Account Management / Security / Access Control / Compliance


  



  

  

  
  

  

  
